# Nginx Port 80 Conflict Troubleshooting Guide

## 📌 Objective

This document outlines the step-by-step troubleshooting process performed to identify and resolve an issue where Nginx failed to start properly due to a port 80 conflict.

---

## 🛠️ Environment Setup

### 1. Installed Docker

```bash
sudo apt install docker.io
docker -v
```

### 2. Cloned Application Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/devopsinsiders/elearn-frontend.git
ls
```

---

## 🌐 Nginx Installation & Initial Setup

### 3. Installed Nginx

```bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt install nginx -y
```

### 4. Attempted to Stop and Check Nginx Service

```bash
systemctl stop nginx
sudo systemctl stop nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

---

## ⚠️ Manual Nginx Execution (Root Cause Begins)

### 5. Started Nginx Manually

```bash
/usr/sbin/nginx
sudo /usr/sbin/nginx
sudo nginx
```

📌 This created Nginx processes outside of systemd control.

---

## 🔍 Issue Identification: Port 80 Already in Use

### 6. Checked Port Usage

```bash
sudo lsof -i :80
```

### 7. Installed Network Tools & Verified Again

```bash
sudo apt install net-tools
sudo netstat -tulnp | grep :80
```

📌 Observation:

* Multiple Nginx processes were already listening on port 80.

---

## 🔁 Service Management Attempts

### 8. Restarted Nginx Service Multiple Times

```bash
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl restart nginx
sudo systemctl stop nginx
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

📌 Issue persisted due to unmanaged processes still running.

---

## 🔎 Process Investigation

### 9. Listed Running Processes

```bash
ps -ef
ps -ef | grep 'nginx'
```

📌 Identified multiple Nginx processes (master + workers).

---

## ❌ Initial Attempt to Kill Process

### 10. Killed Specific Process

```bash
kill -9 3580
sudo kill -9 3580
```

📌 Result:

* Partial success; worker processes or new processes still held port 80.

---

## ✅ Final Resolution

### 11. Force-Killed All Processes Using Port 80

```bash
sudo fuser -k 80/tcp
```

📌 This terminated all processes bound to port 80.

---

### 12. Restarted Nginx Cleanly

```bash
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

✅ Nginx started successfully
✅ Port 80 was free and correctly bound
✅ Service is now managed by systemd

---

## 🧠 Root Cause Analysis

* Nginx was started manually using:

  ```bash
  sudo nginx
  ```
* This bypassed systemd, causing:

  * Multiple unmanaged processes
  * Port 80 conflicts
  * systemctl unable to properly control service

---

## 💡 Key Learnings

* Avoid running Nginx manually (`nginx` command)
* Always use systemd for service management:

  ```bash
  sudo systemctl start nginx
  sudo systemctl stop nginx
  sudo systemctl restart nginx
  ```
* Use the following commands for troubleshooting:

  * Check port usage:

    ```bash
    sudo lsof -i :80
    ```
  * Check processes:

    ```bash
    ps -ef | grep nginx
    ```
  * Kill all processes on a port:

    ```bash
    sudo fuser -k 80/tcp
    ```

---

## 🚀 Quick Fix Command (Future Reference)

```bash
sudo fuser -k 80/tcp
sudo systemctl start nginx
```

